Boil a large #pot{} of salted water for the @rice{150%grams}. Once boiling, add the
rice and @ground turmeric{1/2%sachet}(half the quantity - double for 4p). Cook for
~{10-12%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pot, off the heat.
Cover with a #lid{} and leave aside.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a
#garlic press{}).

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Place a #pan{} over medium-high heat (no oil). Once the pan is hot, fry the
@Irish beef mince{240%grams} until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Mince is cooked
> when no longer pink in the middle.

Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks. Season with @salt{to taste}
and @pepper{to taste}.

Add the garlic and @peas{240%grams} (with a drizzle of @?oil{to taste} if necessary)
and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet}, @chicken stock{1%sachet} and
@korma curry paste{1%sachet} and mix until well combined.

Stir through the @cranberry chutney{1%sachet}.

Stir the rice into the sauce. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.
Add a splash of @water{to taste} if it's a little dry.

When ready, share the beef pilau between #bowls{}.

Finish with a drizzle of @yoghurt{75%grams}.

> This beef and rice pilau is lightly spiced for just the faintest hint of heat.
> It's also infused with a rich and fruity chutney for sweetness and depth of
> flavour that is sure to make this dish a dinnertime hit!